Level of confidence

The below plot show the level of confidence for each technology for the individual part:

The confidence was used to weight the frequency of responses. For instance if 2 people with a confidence level of 3 responded âactiveâ, âactiveâ was counted 6 times (2 x 3), and if another person with a level of confidence of 5 responded âinactiveâ, âinactiveâ was counted 5 times (1 x 5). The information from the second part (groups by pilots) was given a weight of 10. All pilots have group information except the Rhizosphâair aerated french wetland (no group about this pilot was set in the annual meeting).

all the following plots of this section show the weighted frequency of responses for the different parts of the knowledge base, calculated as explained above. The \(n\) shows the number of responses for that pilot in that category. For instance, there were 9 for Ammonia and Aerated + free water surface wetland. Note, that the number of responses for specific value of a technology are usually lower than the number of responses for the level of confidence. The reason is that all attendants answered the level of confidence for almost all technologies, but then left blank the specific values for some technologies, probably because theu did not know the value at all, especially when asking for the surface ratios.

In this section, we present tables with the most frequent value (after weighting) for each technology and feature. In case of equal responses, both are shown in the table. These are the values that we will use in the technology selection tool. In case of deuce, we will use the most conservative option. That is, for instance, if there the same responses for the capacity of a technology to treat ammonia, we will consider the technology cannot treat ammonia. In the case of the ratios to estimate the surface, we will use the weighted mean of all provided values.
